page 157:
we don't expect synonyms (words always differ in meaning slightly, if only by formality or connotation)
if a child hears another word to describe something they already have a word for,
they assume that word refers to another property of that object,
and if they hear that word used to describe another object, 
they will infer that the word refers to a property the two objects share in common

page 117-118:
the head-word of the sentence is its auxiliary verbs, or content words

p167:
phonetic symbolism: inherent meaning to vowel backness

in 1963 Joseph Greenberg discovered many properties universal to all human languages

p413-414:
Donald E Brown's Universal People theory, which establishes a common set of properties universal to all human culture.

The list includes which concepts all cultures have words for!
